{
  "texts": [
    "However, as we illustrated in our previous experiments, reward models themselves can produce inaccurate reward predictions when faced with unfamiliar inputs, which can hinder the effectiveness of RL factuality finetuning.",
    "In this section, we show that strategically controlling how reward models hallucinate can significantly improve the efficacy of RL factuality finetuning for mitigating inaccuracies in long-form model generations.",
    "While reward models hallucinations are inevitable, not all reward hallucinations are necessarily equally harmful to RL factuality finetuning.",
    "We hypothesize that overestimated reward predictions are more harmful than underestimated reward predictions.",
    "To understand why this may be the case, let us consider a reward function that decomposes a long-form response into a set of facts, and assigns a positive reward for every correct fact and a negative reward for every incorrect fact."
  ]
}